00:02:45.600 --> 00:02:48.620
This is the book, which
obviously quite a few of you

00:02:48.620 --> 00:02:49.190
have.

00:02:49.190 --> 00:02:50.530
I'm going to read a
little bit from it.

00:02:50.530 --> 00:02:52.321
I'm going to tell you
a little bit about it

00:02:52.321 --> 00:02:56.300
before I do the reading,
which is that as you know,

00:02:56.300 --> 00:02:59.400
technology is a really
interesting thing.

00:02:59.400 --> 00:03:01.380
And you can do many
things with technology.

00:03:01.380 --> 00:03:03.900
And some of them can be
awesome and some of them

00:03:03.900 --> 00:03:04.970
can be troublesome.

00:03:04.970 --> 00:03:07.490
You know, you
experience it even with,

00:03:07.490 --> 00:03:09.490
like, some of the Google
products that you have.

00:03:09.490 --> 00:03:14.450
On one sense, there are people
who love the fact that, like, I

00:03:14.450 --> 00:03:18.160
can go to Google
Earth or Google Maps

00:03:18.160 --> 00:03:20.130
and actually find a
picture of my house.

00:03:20.130 --> 00:03:21.400
I think that's really awesome.

00:03:21.400 --> 00:03:23.441
I also think that Google
needs to go and redo it,

00:03:23.441 --> 00:03:25.640
because the picture
you took, my lawn

00:03:25.640 --> 00:03:28.670
is yellow because it
was like early March.

00:03:28.670 --> 00:03:31.860
And my trash can is tipped
over in front of my house.

00:03:31.860 --> 00:03:35.380
This is not how I want
the world to see my house,

00:03:35.380 --> 00:03:40.052
so please, Google
Maps, go fix that.

00:03:40.052 --> 00:03:41.510
But some people
think it's awesome.

00:03:41.510 --> 00:03:43.530
On the other hand,
there are some people

00:03:43.530 --> 00:03:47.150
who feel that all this is
somehow an invasion of privacy.

00:03:47.150 --> 00:03:48.969
I think in Europe,
they had some people

00:03:48.969 --> 00:03:51.260
who were like there's some
places where they don't want

00:03:51.260 --> 00:03:52.740
you to map or
something like that.

00:03:52.740 --> 00:03:55.150
The folks over here with
Google Glass-- in one sense,

00:03:55.150 --> 00:03:58.870
it's awesome that you can
walk around and actually

00:03:58.870 --> 00:04:01.610
have that stuff without having
your phone directly in front

00:04:01.610 --> 00:04:03.610
of you, and therefore,
walking into trees.

00:04:03.610 --> 00:04:05.860
On the other hand, there are
some people who are like,

00:04:05.860 --> 00:04:08.190
will you please turn
those things off?

00:04:08.190 --> 00:04:10.800
Because they don't know if
you are running the pictures

00:04:10.800 --> 00:04:11.580
live or not.

00:04:11.580 --> 00:04:15.270
So there's always that back and
forth about what technology is

00:04:15.270 --> 00:04:17.070
and how we integrated
it into our lives.

00:04:17.070 --> 00:04:19.670
And it's really interesting
to me, quite frankly,

00:04:19.670 --> 00:04:24.880
just how quickly you get
used to how technology just

00:04:24.880 --> 00:04:26.900
is integral to your life.

00:04:26.900 --> 00:04:32.270
Like my Google phone
here from Motorola,

00:04:32.270 --> 00:04:34.600
which you dearly departed.

00:04:34.600 --> 00:04:38.860
And so, the thing that is
awesome about this piece

00:04:38.860 --> 00:04:42.910
of technology is not that I
can talk to it and say, "Hey,

00:04:42.910 --> 00:04:47.970
Google Now,"-- turn that
off-- and have it respond.

00:04:47.970 --> 00:04:50.940
And I will ask it a question
and it will give me an answer.

00:04:50.940 --> 00:04:53.420
What is awesome is that I
can say, "Hey, Google Now,"

00:04:53.420 --> 00:04:57.810
and ask it a question
and give me an answer,

00:04:57.810 --> 00:05:00.090
and if it gets it
wrong, I get annoyed.

00:05:00.090 --> 00:05:00.620
Right?

00:05:00.620 --> 00:05:03.230
And what that means is--
why that's so cool--

00:05:03.230 --> 00:05:04.820
is that I'm so
used to this being

00:05:04.820 --> 00:05:08.190
an integral part of my life-- of
living in the future, of having

00:05:08.190 --> 00:05:10.520
the entire world
at my doorstep--

00:05:10.520 --> 00:05:12.410
that frankly, when the
technology does not

00:05:12.410 --> 00:05:16.280
work the way it's supposed
to that I can get annoyed.

00:05:16.280 --> 00:05:20.230
That the wonder of all
this technology, the wonder

00:05:20.230 --> 00:05:24.670
of everything that science
has wrought and that you guys

00:05:24.670 --> 00:05:27.010
work on on a day
in, day out basis

00:05:27.010 --> 00:05:29.250
will just piss me off when
it's not working exactly

00:05:29.250 --> 00:05:30.560
the way it's supposed to.

00:05:30.560 --> 00:05:32.470
That means we are
living in the future

00:05:32.470 --> 00:05:36.010
because it is just part
of our everyday lives.

00:05:36.010 --> 00:05:37.680
And "Lock In" is about that.

00:05:37.680 --> 00:05:42.060
What happens is that the day
after tomorrow, as they say,

00:05:42.060 --> 00:05:45.780
there is a new disease that's
sweeps around the world.

00:05:45.780 --> 00:05:48.630
And so, let's say
everybody in this room

00:05:48.630 --> 00:05:50.620
gets sick with this disease.

00:05:50.620 --> 00:05:52.200
At first, it's like a flu.

00:05:52.200 --> 00:05:54.990
So you all get sick, right?

00:05:54.990 --> 00:05:59.550
About, let's say, everybody
but the first three rows

00:05:59.550 --> 00:06:00.870
here gets better.

00:06:00.870 --> 00:06:02.770
You get sick, you get
better, it's the flu.

00:06:02.770 --> 00:06:03.870
Not a problem.

00:06:03.870 --> 00:06:07.750
But these folks in
the first three rows,

00:06:07.750 --> 00:06:11.140
you get to the second
phase of the disease.

00:06:11.140 --> 00:06:13.650
And what that is like
viral meningitis.

00:06:13.650 --> 00:06:16.680
And your brain swells up
and it's really painful.

00:06:16.680 --> 00:06:19.300
And then some of you drop dead.

00:06:19.300 --> 00:06:20.100
Let's say--

00:06:20.100 --> 00:06:22.450
[AUDIENCE LAUGHTER]

00:06:22.450 --> 00:06:25.710
Those folks, sorry, you're dead.

00:06:25.710 --> 00:06:27.646
And these folks are still alive.

00:06:27.646 --> 00:06:29.270
And of these folks
who are still alive,

00:06:29.270 --> 00:06:31.980
there is a third stage,
which is called lock in.

00:06:31.980 --> 00:06:39.670
And lock in means that your
entire autonomic system

00:06:39.670 --> 00:06:40.570
breaks down.

00:06:40.570 --> 00:06:44.840
Your brain is still
functioning but you are not

00:06:44.840 --> 00:06:45.676
able to do anything.

00:06:45.676 --> 00:06:47.550
You are literally locked
inside of your body.

00:06:47.550 --> 00:06:49.470
And so, it's about
1% of the people.

00:06:49.470 --> 00:06:52.020
So you and you.

00:06:52.020 --> 00:06:52.800
You are locked in.

00:06:52.800 --> 00:06:56.050
Sorry, Chris.

00:06:56.050 --> 00:06:58.400
And so, in one sort
of sense, it doesn't

00:06:58.400 --> 00:07:00.980
seem like that many
people altogether.

00:07:00.980 --> 00:07:06.821
But if it's these two in a
room of 200 people replicated

00:07:06.821 --> 00:07:08.320
all across the
country, that ends up

00:07:08.320 --> 00:07:11.360
being 1% of the population
maybe like at the time.

00:07:11.360 --> 00:07:14.850
Let's say about
4.35 million people,

00:07:14.850 --> 00:07:18.736
which is the city of Los Angeles
or the state of Connecticut.

00:07:18.736 --> 00:07:21.360
And then, all of the sudden, it
becomes this huge public health

00:07:21.360 --> 00:07:21.859
crisis.

00:07:21.859 --> 00:07:22.880
And how do we solve it?

00:07:22.880 --> 00:07:27.260
How do we get them
out of their minds,

00:07:27.260 --> 00:07:29.650
so to speak, in a
very literal sense?

00:07:29.650 --> 00:07:31.700
And the answer is--
and this is something

00:07:31.700 --> 00:07:35.000
the folks here at Google would
know-- is you throw technology

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:37.190
at it and also a lot of money.

00:07:37.190 --> 00:07:40.760
And so there's this
research initiative that

00:07:40.760 --> 00:07:43.680
includes brain prosthesis,
you know neural networks

00:07:43.680 --> 00:07:46.350
within your brain--
integrating with your brain--

00:07:46.350 --> 00:07:51.900
a multiple online place for
the people who are locked in

00:07:51.900 --> 00:07:53.770
to have some semblance
of conversation

00:07:53.770 --> 00:07:55.540
amongst each other,
and then these things

00:07:55.540 --> 00:07:59.880
called Threeps-- which are
named after C3PO-- that they

00:07:59.880 --> 00:08:02.940
are basically androids that they
drive around with their brains.

00:08:02.940 --> 00:08:07.680
So Chris is locked in, but
he will have this really cool

00:08:07.680 --> 00:08:12.960
looking android--
ironically enough--

00:08:12.960 --> 00:08:16.920
and he will wander around
and do all the stuff

00:08:16.920 --> 00:08:20.740
that he does in the android
while his body is at home being

00:08:20.740 --> 00:08:21.400
tended to.

00:08:21.400 --> 00:08:23.650
And the thing is, is when
it first happens, of course,

00:08:23.650 --> 00:08:24.920
it's the most amazing thing.

00:08:24.920 --> 00:08:27.900
We've turned you
into an android.

00:08:27.900 --> 00:08:30.719
25 years on-- which is
when this happens-- nobody

00:08:30.719 --> 00:08:32.260
cares that you're
an android anymore,

00:08:32.260 --> 00:08:35.039
you're just part of the world.

00:08:35.039 --> 00:08:37.240
1% of everybody in the
world is an android.

00:08:37.240 --> 00:08:40.030
And how do you deal with that
and where do you go from there?

00:08:40.030 --> 00:08:41.280
So that was interesting to me.

00:08:41.280 --> 00:08:43.549
The thing that interests
me about technology

00:08:43.549 --> 00:08:46.530
is not how awesome
the technology is.

00:08:46.530 --> 00:08:50.160
It is what happens after
the awesome wears out.

00:08:50.160 --> 00:08:54.700
You know, when it just becomes
part of your day-to-day life

00:08:54.700 --> 00:08:58.390
and you deal with this stuff
and it's not that big of a deal.

00:08:58.390 --> 00:09:03.110
And the most that you
think about your technology

00:09:03.110 --> 00:09:05.790
is when it's not doing
what it's supposed to do.

00:09:05.790 --> 00:09:07.610
And to give an idea
of kind of what

00:09:07.610 --> 00:09:13.630
that would be like to be someone
who is dealing with this stuff,

00:09:13.630 --> 00:09:20.000
I'm going to read a quick
chapter from chapter five

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:23.390
where our protagonist,
Chris Shane,

00:09:23.390 --> 00:09:25.480
is looking for an apartment.

00:09:28.070 --> 00:09:31.240
Chris is someone
who is a Haden-- who

00:09:31.240 --> 00:09:32.980
is one of these people
who is locked in--

00:09:32.980 --> 00:09:37.040
and so when Chris is
looking for someplace,

00:09:37.040 --> 00:09:40.310
it has to be some place
that actually caters

00:09:40.310 --> 00:09:43.167
to the needs of someone
who is locked in.

00:09:43.167 --> 00:09:45.000
So I'm going to go ahead
and read from that.

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:49.900
And just so you know, Chris
is part of a famous family.

00:09:49.900 --> 00:09:54.070
So Chris would be
very much like someone

00:09:54.070 --> 00:09:57.260
who is like a child
star at one point

00:09:57.260 --> 00:09:59.720
and stops being that
child star and tries

00:09:59.720 --> 00:10:00.880
to have a normal life.

00:10:00.880 --> 00:10:03.870
And right now Chris works
for the FBI, first couple

00:10:03.870 --> 00:10:10.690
days on the job, he's trying
to get a new apartment in DC.

00:10:10.690 --> 00:10:14.080
The Realtor was a small, elegant
woman named LaTasha Robinson,

00:10:14.080 --> 00:10:16.890
and she met me directly
outside the Bureau building.

00:10:16.890 --> 00:10:19.760
One of her Realty specialties
was the Haden market,

00:10:19.760 --> 00:10:21.790
so the Bureau connected
me with her to help me

00:10:21.790 --> 00:10:23.030
find an apartment.

00:10:23.030 --> 00:10:25.440
Given her clientele, the
chances that she might not

00:10:25.440 --> 00:10:28.240
know who I was were close
to nil, a suspicion that

00:10:28.240 --> 00:10:30.040
was verified as I approached.

00:10:30.040 --> 00:10:31.840
She smiled the
smile I recognized

00:10:31.840 --> 00:10:35.090
from years of being trotted out
as the official Haden's poster

00:10:35.090 --> 00:10:38.690
child, part of the official
Haden's poster family.

00:10:38.690 --> 00:10:40.690
I didn't hold it against her.

00:10:40.690 --> 00:10:43.090
"Agent Shane," she said,
holding out her hand.

00:10:43.090 --> 00:10:45.260
"Really lovely to meet you."

00:10:45.260 --> 00:10:48.410
I took the hand and shook
it. "Ms. Robinson, likewise."

00:10:48.410 --> 00:10:48.910
"I'm sorry.

00:10:48.910 --> 00:10:51.170
This is just kind of
exciting," she said.

00:10:51.170 --> 00:10:53.180
"I don't need that
many famous people,

00:10:53.180 --> 00:10:55.010
I mean, who aren't
politicians."--

00:10:55.010 --> 00:10:56.690
This takes place in DC--

00:10:56.690 --> 00:10:59.150
"Not in this town,
no," I agreed.

00:10:59.150 --> 00:11:01.380
"And I don't think of
politicians as being famous,

00:11:01.380 --> 00:11:01.960
do you?

00:11:01.960 --> 00:11:04.620
They're just politicians."

00:11:04.620 --> 00:11:06.390
"I couldn't agree more."

00:11:06.390 --> 00:11:08.050
"My car's right over
here," she said,

00:11:08.050 --> 00:11:10.590
pointing to a relatively
unflashy Cadillac parked

00:11:10.590 --> 00:11:11.940
where it would get ticketed.

00:11:11.940 --> 00:11:13.620
"Why don't we get started?"

00:11:13.620 --> 00:11:15.330
I got into the passenger side.

00:11:15.330 --> 00:11:18.620
Robinson got into the driver's
seat and pulled out her tablet.

00:11:18.620 --> 00:11:20.850
"Amble," she said,
and the car slid out

00:11:20.850 --> 00:11:22.630
from the curve
just ahead, I noted

00:11:22.630 --> 00:11:25.710
as I glanced in the rear-view
mirror, of a traffic cop.

00:11:25.710 --> 00:11:27.949
We headed east on
Pennsylvania Avenue.

00:11:27.949 --> 00:11:30.240
"The car's just going to
drive around for a few minutes

00:11:30.240 --> 00:11:31.850
while we get set
up here," Robinson

00:11:31.850 --> 00:11:33.470
said, tapping her tablet.

00:11:33.470 --> 00:11:35.640
For all her gushing
a few seconds before,

00:11:35.640 --> 00:11:38.041
she slipped into business
mode pretty quickly.

00:11:38.041 --> 00:11:40.540
"I've got your basic request
list and personal information."

00:11:40.540 --> 00:11:42.210
She looked over as
if to acknowledge

00:11:42.210 --> 00:11:45.100
that I was, in fact, a
Haden and she knew it.

00:11:45.100 --> 00:11:48.170
"So let's get a few things
narrowed down before we start."

00:11:48.170 --> 00:11:49.610
"All right," I said.

00:11:49.610 --> 00:11:51.730
"So how close do you
want to be to work?"

00:11:51.730 --> 00:11:53.020
"Closer is better."

00:11:53.020 --> 00:11:57.630
"Are we talking walking-close
or Metro line-close?"

00:11:57.630 --> 00:11:59.580
"Metro line-close
is fine," I said.

00:11:59.580 --> 00:12:01.080
"Do you prefer a
neighborhood that's

00:12:01.080 --> 00:12:02.900
hip or one that's quiet?"

00:12:02.900 --> 00:12:04.640
"It doesn't really
matter to me."

00:12:04.640 --> 00:12:06.450
"You say that now,
but if I get you

00:12:06.450 --> 00:12:09.380
an apartment over a bar in
Adams Morgan and you hate it,

00:12:09.380 --> 00:12:11.500
you're going to
blame me," Robinson

00:12:11.500 --> 00:12:13.220
said looking over at me.

00:12:13.220 --> 00:12:15.250
"I promise, noise isn't
going to bother me,"

00:12:15.250 --> 00:12:17.920
I said. "I can turn
down my hearing."

00:12:17.920 --> 00:12:20.450
"Do you plan on using the
apartment to socialize?"

00:12:20.450 --> 00:12:23.640
"Not really," I said. "I do most
of my socializing elsewhere.

00:12:23.640 --> 00:12:26.210
I might have a friend
over from time to time."

00:12:26.210 --> 00:12:28.160
Robinson looked
over again at this

00:12:28.160 --> 00:12:29.970
and seemed to be
considering whether to ask

00:12:29.970 --> 00:12:32.780
for clarification and
decided against it.

00:12:32.780 --> 00:12:34.230
It was a fair call.

00:12:34.230 --> 00:12:36.010
There were Threep
fetishists out there.

00:12:36.010 --> 00:12:38.910
They weren't really my
thing, I have to say.

00:12:38.910 --> 00:12:41.420
"Will your body be physically
present, and if so,

00:12:41.420 --> 00:12:44.060
will you need room for
a caretaker?" she asked.

00:12:44.060 --> 00:12:47.200
"My body and its care-taking are
already squared away," I said.

00:12:47.200 --> 00:12:49.560
"We won't be needing
space for either, at least

00:12:49.560 --> 00:12:51.160
not right away."

00:12:51.160 --> 00:12:53.590
"In that case, I have some
Haden efficiency flats

00:12:53.590 --> 00:12:55.540
on my availability
list," she said.

00:12:55.540 --> 00:12:57.429
"Would you like to see those?"

00:12:57.429 --> 00:12:58.470
"Are they worth my time?"

00:12:58.470 --> 00:12:59.350
I asked.

00:12:59.350 --> 00:13:00.630
Robinson shrugged.

00:13:00.630 --> 00:13:02.137
"Some Hadens like
them," she said.

00:13:02.137 --> 00:13:04.220
"I think they're a little
small, but then, they're

00:13:04.220 --> 00:13:06.450
not designed for non-Hadens."

00:13:06.450 --> 00:13:08.410
"Are they close by?"

00:13:08.410 --> 00:13:11.030
"I've got a building of them
on D Avenue in Southwest,

00:13:11.030 --> 00:13:13.377
right by Federal Center
Metro," Robinson said.

00:13:13.377 --> 00:13:15.210
"The Department of
Health and Human Services

00:13:15.210 --> 00:13:18.809
hires a lot of Hadens, so it's
convenient housing for them."

00:13:18.809 --> 00:13:21.100
"All right," I said. "We
might as well check them out."

00:13:21.100 --> 00:13:24.350
"We'll go there first," Robinson
said, and spoke the address

00:13:24.350 --> 00:13:25.710
to the Cadillac.

00:13:25.710 --> 00:13:27.210
Five minutes later,
we were in front

00:13:27.210 --> 00:13:29.810
of a depressing slab
of anonymous brutalist

00:13:29.810 --> 00:13:31.370
architecture.

00:13:31.370 --> 00:13:33.942
"This is lovely," I said dryly.

00:13:33.942 --> 00:13:36.150
"I think it used to be a
government office building,"

00:13:36.150 --> 00:13:38.817
Robinson said. "They converted
it about 20 years ago.

00:13:38.817 --> 00:13:40.650
It was one of the first
buildings redesigned

00:13:40.650 --> 00:13:42.150
with Hadens in mind."

00:13:42.150 --> 00:13:45.850
She nodded me into the lobby,
which was clean and plain.

00:13:45.850 --> 00:13:48.120
A Threep receptionist
sat behind a desk.

00:13:48.120 --> 00:13:50.210
The Threep was set
to transmit ID data

00:13:50.210 --> 00:13:51.780
over the common channel.

00:13:51.780 --> 00:13:53.580
In my field of vision,
it's owner's data

00:13:53.580 --> 00:13:55.660
popped up above
the Threeps head--

00:13:55.660 --> 00:13:59.360
Genevieve Tourneaux,
27 years old, native

00:13:59.360 --> 00:14:00.720
of Rockville, Maryland.

00:14:00.720 --> 00:14:03.350
Her public address
for direct messages.

00:14:03.350 --> 00:14:05.220
"Hello," Robinson
said to Genevieve,

00:14:05.220 --> 00:14:07.670
and showed her her Realtors ID.

00:14:07.670 --> 00:14:10.530
"We're here to look at the
vacancy on the fifth floor."

00:14:10.530 --> 00:14:12.830
Genevieve turned to me
and I realized belatedly

00:14:12.830 --> 00:14:15.360
that I didn't have my
own personal data out

00:14:15.360 --> 00:14:16.700
on the common channel.

00:14:16.700 --> 00:14:18.510
Some Hadens found that rude.

00:14:18.510 --> 00:14:20.200
I quickly popped it up.

00:14:20.200 --> 00:14:22.470
She gave me a quick nod
as if an acknowledgement,

00:14:22.470 --> 00:14:24.600
did a small double-take,
then recovered

00:14:24.600 --> 00:14:26.580
and turned her
attention to Robinson.

00:14:26.580 --> 00:14:30.590
"Unit 503 is unlocked for the
next 15 minutes," she said.

00:14:30.590 --> 00:14:33.590
"Thank you," Robinson said
and nodded over to me.

00:14:33.590 --> 00:14:35.130
"Hold on a second," I said.

00:14:35.130 --> 00:14:36.870
I turned back to Genevieve.

00:14:36.870 --> 00:14:40.550
"May I have guest access to
the building channel, please?"

00:14:40.550 --> 00:14:43.310
Genevieve nodded to me and I
saw the channel marker pop up

00:14:43.310 --> 00:14:44.840
in my field of view.

00:14:44.840 --> 00:14:46.720
I connected to it.

00:14:46.720 --> 00:14:49.890
The lobby walls
exploded into signage.

00:14:49.890 --> 00:14:52.590
Some of the notes were your
basic cork board notes-- people

00:14:52.590 --> 00:14:54.180
looking for roommates
or to sublet

00:14:54.180 --> 00:14:56.010
or asking after lost pets.

00:14:56.010 --> 00:14:58.430
At the moment, however, signs
about the walk-out in March

00:14:58.430 --> 00:14:59.210
dominated.

00:14:59.210 --> 00:15:01.230
Signs reminding
tenants to stay home,

00:15:01.230 --> 00:15:03.270
plans for walk-out
activities, requests

00:15:03.270 --> 00:15:06.340
to let Hadens coming
into town for the march

00:15:06.340 --> 00:15:09.560
crash in apartments with
the sardonic notation

00:15:09.560 --> 00:15:11.980
that they would not
need much space.

00:15:11.980 --> 00:15:12.920
"Is everything OK?"

00:15:12.920 --> 00:15:14.410
Robinson asked.

00:15:14.410 --> 00:15:15.710
"It's fine," I said.

00:15:15.710 --> 00:15:18.122
"I'm just taking in the
posters on the wall."

00:15:18.122 --> 00:15:19.830
I read a few more and
then we walked over

00:15:19.830 --> 00:15:23.640
to the elevator bank and took
the lift up to the fifth floor.

00:15:23.640 --> 00:15:26.340
"Extra large elevators,"
Robinson noted as we rose.

00:15:26.340 --> 00:15:27.660
"Hydraulic lift.

00:15:27.660 --> 00:15:30.960
Makes it easier to bring
bodies up to the room."

00:15:30.960 --> 00:15:33.600
"I thought these were all
efficiency apartments," I said.

00:15:33.600 --> 00:15:35.690
"No, not all of
them," Robinson said.

00:15:35.690 --> 00:15:38.310
"Some of them are full-sized and
have dedicated medical suites

00:15:38.310 --> 00:15:39.580
and caretaker rooms.

00:15:39.580 --> 00:15:41.960
Even the efficiencies
have cradle hookups.

00:15:41.960 --> 00:15:44.180
They're supposed to be
used on a temp basis,

00:15:44.180 --> 00:15:47.560
although I hear some Hadens
are using them full time now."

00:15:47.560 --> 00:15:49.060
"And why is that?"

00:15:49.060 --> 00:15:51.280
The elevator stopped
and the doors opened.

00:15:51.280 --> 00:15:54.650
"Abrams Kettering"-- which is
a bill that has been passed

00:15:54.650 --> 00:15:57.660
that will cut government
funding for Hadens research

00:15:57.660 --> 00:16:01.890
and medical services--

00:16:01.890 --> 00:16:03.540
"Adams Kettering,"
Robinson said.

00:16:03.540 --> 00:16:05.990
She walked out of the
lift and down the hall.

00:16:05.990 --> 00:16:08.120
"Assistance is getting
slashed so a lot of Hadens

00:16:08.120 --> 00:16:09.140
are downsizing.

00:16:09.140 --> 00:16:11.880
Those in town homes are moving
into smaller apartments.

00:16:11.880 --> 00:16:14.550
Those in apartments are
moving into efficiencies.

00:16:14.550 --> 00:16:16.070
And some of those
in efficiencies

00:16:16.070 --> 00:16:17.460
are taking on roommates.

00:16:17.460 --> 00:16:19.782
They're using the
chargers in shifts."

00:16:19.782 --> 00:16:21.240
She glanced back
to me and her eyes

00:16:21.240 --> 00:16:24.240
flickered over my shiny,
expensive Threep as if to say,

00:16:24.240 --> 00:16:26.577
not that you have
to worry about that.

00:16:26.577 --> 00:16:28.410
"It's been bad for the
market, to be honest.

00:16:28.410 --> 00:16:30.480
But that's good for you
as a potential renter.

00:16:30.480 --> 00:16:33.540
Now you have a lot more
options a lot cheaper."

00:16:33.540 --> 00:16:35.480
She stopped at apartment 503.

00:16:35.480 --> 00:16:38.060
"That is if this
doesn't bowl you over."

00:16:38.060 --> 00:16:41.700
She opened the door and stood
aside to let me pass through.

00:16:41.700 --> 00:16:45.890
Haden efficiency apartment 503
was two meters by three meters

00:16:45.890 --> 00:16:49.670
and entirely bare save for
one built-in counter top.

00:16:49.670 --> 00:16:53.760
I stepped inside and
immediately got claustrophobia.

00:16:53.760 --> 00:16:55.710
"This isn't an apartment,
it's a closet,"

00:16:55.710 --> 00:16:58.930
I said, stepping forward
to let Robinson in.

00:16:58.930 --> 00:17:00.490
"I usually think of
it as a bathroom"

00:17:00.490 --> 00:17:03.270
Robinson said, and pointed
to a small tiled area which

00:17:03.270 --> 00:17:06.839
had a bank of electrical outlets
and a couple of covered drains

00:17:06.839 --> 00:17:08.740
on the floor flush
with the tile.

00:17:08.740 --> 00:17:10.970
"That would be the
medical nook, by the way.

00:17:10.970 --> 00:17:12.970
Right where the
toilet would be."

00:17:12.970 --> 00:17:15.270
"You're not exactly
giving me the hard sell

00:17:15.270 --> 00:17:17.780
on this apartment,
Ms Robinson," I said.

00:17:17.780 --> 00:17:20.990
"Well, to be fair, if
all you're looking to do

00:17:20.990 --> 00:17:23.710
is park your Threep every
night, this isn't a bad choice,"

00:17:23.710 --> 00:17:24.729
Robinson said.

00:17:24.729 --> 00:17:26.270
She pointed to the
back right corner,

00:17:26.270 --> 00:17:28.020
where the grooves and
high voltage outlets

00:17:28.020 --> 00:17:32.100
were set into the wall ready
to receive inductive chargers.

00:17:32.100 --> 00:17:33.920
"It's designed with
standard Threep cradles

00:17:33.920 --> 00:17:36.270
in mind and the hard wired
and wireless networks

00:17:36.270 --> 00:17:38.210
are fast and have
deep throughput.

00:17:38.210 --> 00:17:40.790
The spaces have been
designed with Threeps in mind

00:17:40.790 --> 00:17:42.710
so you don't have
inessential things taking up

00:17:42.710 --> 00:17:45.510
space like closets or sinks.

00:17:45.510 --> 00:17:50.460
It's everything you need and
absolutely nothing you don't."

00:17:50.460 --> 00:17:52.960
"I hate it," I said.

00:17:52.960 --> 00:17:54.630
"I thought you
might," Robinson said.

00:17:54.630 --> 00:17:57.100
"That's why I showed
it to you first.

00:17:57.100 --> 00:17:58.730
Now that we have
that out of the way,

00:17:58.730 --> 00:18:00.771
we can show you something
that you might actually

00:18:00.771 --> 00:18:01.980
be interested in."

00:18:01.980 --> 00:18:03.780
I stared back at
the spot of tile

00:18:03.780 --> 00:18:05.700
and thought about
putting a human body

00:18:05.700 --> 00:18:08.410
there more or less permanently.

00:18:08.410 --> 00:18:10.420
"So these kind of apartments
are hot right now?"

00:18:10.420 --> 00:18:11.520
I asked.

00:18:11.520 --> 00:18:14.590
"They are," Robinson said. "I
don't usually deal with them.

00:18:14.590 --> 00:18:16.290
Not enough commission on them.

00:18:16.290 --> 00:18:19.580
They usually get rented
through online want ads,

00:18:19.580 --> 00:18:22.380
but yes, right now,
this kind of apartment

00:18:22.380 --> 00:18:24.920
is selling like hotcakes."

00:18:24.920 --> 00:18:27.470
"Well, now I'm feeling a
little depressed," I said.

00:18:27.470 --> 00:18:29.880
"Well, you don't have to feel
depressed," Robinson said.

00:18:29.880 --> 00:18:31.730
"You're not going to live here.

00:18:31.730 --> 00:18:34.330
You're not going to
have your body in here."

00:18:34.330 --> 00:18:36.780
"But apparently some
people are," I said.

00:18:36.780 --> 00:18:38.300
"Yes," Robinson said.

00:18:38.300 --> 00:18:40.880
"Maybe it's a blessing that
the bodies don't notice."

00:18:40.880 --> 00:18:43.670
"Ah, but that's
not true," I said.

00:18:43.670 --> 00:18:46.220
"We're locked in, but
we're not unconscious.

00:18:46.220 --> 00:18:49.710
Trust me, Ms Robinson, we
notice where our bodies are.

00:18:49.710 --> 00:18:52.630
We notice it every
moment we're awake."

00:18:52.630 --> 00:18:54.180
All right, so that's that.

00:18:54.180 --> 00:18:55.605
[AUDIENCE APPLAUSE]

00:19:01.790 --> 00:19:03.460
And like I said,
one of the things

00:19:03.460 --> 00:19:06.480
that you can see from
that particular thing

00:19:06.480 --> 00:19:10.290
is this is someone who is just
trying to find an apartment.

00:19:10.290 --> 00:19:15.040
But an apartment that conforms
to the reality of their life

00:19:15.040 --> 00:19:16.200
situation.

00:19:16.200 --> 00:19:18.672
That there is an
android that they

00:19:18.672 --> 00:19:20.380
will use to get around
in the real world,

00:19:20.380 --> 00:19:22.390
but there needs to be
a space for the body.

00:19:22.390 --> 00:19:26.260
And that body will need to have
a caretaker looking after it

00:19:26.260 --> 00:19:29.940
while the owner of the
body is, literally,

00:19:29.940 --> 00:19:31.490
somewhere else in the world.

00:19:31.490 --> 00:19:34.660
And like I said, on
a day-to-day basis,

00:19:34.660 --> 00:19:36.330
this is just the life they lead.

00:19:36.330 --> 00:19:41.220
For us reading a book about
the future, this is all new

00:19:41.220 --> 00:19:43.300
and this is all cool, right?

00:19:43.300 --> 00:19:46.020
But one of the things you
have to really do as a writer,

00:19:46.020 --> 00:19:52.430
you really want to try to avoid
is making a big deal out of it

00:19:52.430 --> 00:19:54.190
for the people who
are living in there.

00:19:54.190 --> 00:19:55.981
One of the things that
science fiction does

00:19:55.981 --> 00:19:57.670
really badly is the
exposition trap,

00:19:57.670 --> 00:19:59.800
which is the "As you know, Bob."

00:19:59.800 --> 00:20:02.010
Where you go, you
know, "As you know,

00:20:02.010 --> 00:20:05.720
Chris, we are here at Google,
this worldwide technological

00:20:05.720 --> 00:20:09.110
company that was founded on
the search engine thing."

00:20:09.110 --> 00:20:10.820
and you'd be like,
"Oh, yes, absolutely."

00:20:10.820 --> 00:20:11.960
He knows that.

00:20:11.960 --> 00:20:14.370
He's been working
here for 10 years.

00:20:14.370 --> 00:20:16.250
But in fiction, you
see a lot of that

00:20:16.250 --> 00:20:18.370
because the audience
doesn't know that.

00:20:18.370 --> 00:20:20.490
You have to give that
information while

00:20:20.490 --> 00:20:21.990
at the same time
respecting the fact

00:20:21.990 --> 00:20:27.680
that the characters that you are
following and creating actually

00:20:27.680 --> 00:20:30.690
have all of this internalized.

00:20:30.690 --> 00:20:34.230
One of the defining challenges
of writing science fiction

00:20:34.230 --> 00:20:38.040
is to establish for the
reader in the present time

00:20:38.040 --> 00:20:41.210
this awesome technology while
at the same time establishing

00:20:41.210 --> 00:20:43.400
for the characters who
live in that future

00:20:43.400 --> 00:20:44.970
that this is their life.

00:20:44.970 --> 00:20:45.850
Right?

00:20:45.850 --> 00:20:48.210
That this magnificent
technology is

00:20:48.210 --> 00:20:53.190
no more exciting to them as
than a cellphone or a DVR,

00:20:53.190 --> 00:20:55.130
which both of which,
if you think about it,

00:20:55.130 --> 00:20:56.600
are pretty damn awesome.

00:20:56.600 --> 00:21:02.000
If I went back 25 years ago
and told the 20-year-old me

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:05.846
about a cellphone, I would
be like, "Are you a wizard?"

00:21:05.846 --> 00:21:06.345
You know?

00:21:06.345 --> 00:21:09.980
You Think about it-- remember
Star Trek, the original Star

00:21:09.980 --> 00:21:12.430
Trek, where Kirk's
got a communicator.

00:21:12.430 --> 00:21:15.340
And you're like, oh,
so it only does voice.

00:21:15.340 --> 00:21:16.850
That's cute.

00:21:16.850 --> 00:21:22.240
Because it's like my phone
here does voice, it does text,

00:21:22.240 --> 00:21:25.440
it takes pictures, it
does-- it's basically,

00:21:25.440 --> 00:21:27.990
you can use it now
as a tricorder.

00:21:27.990 --> 00:21:30.740
Quite frankly, if you've got
one of those Google Gear things

00:21:30.740 --> 00:21:33.080
that's got, you can
check your heart rate,

00:21:33.080 --> 00:21:35.430
you can see what's
going on with your body.

00:21:35.430 --> 00:21:39.660
And so that communicator
that Kirk had back in 1967,

00:21:39.660 --> 00:21:45.450
but supposedly the 23rd century,
is just unbelievably quaint.

00:21:45.450 --> 00:21:49.980
So it's just a fascinating thing
about how the future catches up

00:21:49.980 --> 00:21:51.930
with you and how, as a
science fiction writer,

00:21:51.930 --> 00:21:53.680
you deal with that.

00:21:53.680 --> 00:21:58.810
So what I'm trying to say
is that, when you read this,

00:21:58.810 --> 00:22:02.520
I hope what you get out of it
is that this feature is cool.

00:22:02.520 --> 00:22:04.420
But for them, it's
just another day

00:22:04.420 --> 00:22:07.510
with a whole different
set of problems.

00:22:07.510 --> 00:22:10.960
We are, I think, about
at the half hour point,

00:22:10.960 --> 00:22:13.910
which means that it's time to
actually open up to questions

00:22:13.910 --> 00:22:15.471
from you folks here at Google.

00:22:15.471 --> 00:22:17.220
And I'll be happy to
talk about "Lock In."

00:22:17.220 --> 00:22:19.840
I'll be happy to talk about
the other books that I have.

00:22:19.840 --> 00:22:22.260
I'll be happy to talk
about the TV series that

00:22:22.260 --> 00:22:23.970
are being developed
out of a couple

00:22:23.970 --> 00:22:26.070
of my books or the video game.

