00:23:07.552 --> 00:23:09.760
AUDIENCE: Specifically in
the "Old Man's War" series,

00:23:09.760 --> 00:23:11.632
something that I
noticed in your writing

00:23:11.632 --> 00:23:13.340
that I don't see in
a lot of other places

00:23:13.340 --> 00:23:15.769
is that you portray
people who are married

00:23:15.769 --> 00:23:17.310
or have been married
for a long time,

00:23:17.310 --> 00:23:21.295
longstanding
relationships as opposed

00:23:21.295 --> 00:23:22.850
to simply the chase portion.

00:23:22.850 --> 00:23:25.450
This seems-- I don't want
to say unique in fiction,

00:23:25.450 --> 00:23:27.040
but pretty rare.

00:23:27.040 --> 00:23:31.040
What brought you to do that, and
why you and pretty much nobody

00:23:31.040 --> 00:23:31.707
else.

00:23:31.707 --> 00:23:33.790
JOHN SCALZI: I don't know
that I would necessarily

00:23:33.790 --> 00:23:37.840
agree with that particular
premise, because for example,

00:23:37.840 --> 00:23:41.620
in "Forever War", there is
a longstanding relationship

00:23:41.620 --> 00:23:45.110
between the protagonist
and Mary Gay

00:23:45.110 --> 00:23:50.020
who, interestingly enough,
has a very near name

00:23:50.020 --> 00:23:53.510
of Joe Holdeman's wife, Gay.

00:23:53.510 --> 00:23:56.300
And so, for me
also-- I mean, I've

00:23:56.300 --> 00:24:00.180
been married for a certain
number of years, going up

00:24:00.180 --> 00:24:01.780
on 20 years now.

00:24:01.780 --> 00:24:06.490
My wife is, actually, the
template for Jane Sagan.

00:24:06.490 --> 00:24:07.640
Right?

00:24:07.640 --> 00:24:12.310
So when you imagine Jane Sagan,
imagine a woman who's about

00:24:12.310 --> 00:24:16.680
5'10", straight,
brown hair, you know,

00:24:16.680 --> 00:24:20.130
and will kill you if
you get in her way.

00:24:20.130 --> 00:24:22.190
Because that is my wife.

00:24:22.190 --> 00:24:26.790
She is no-nonsense, super
awesome, and when it came to,

00:24:26.790 --> 00:24:29.110
I need to develop this
bad ass character,

00:24:29.110 --> 00:24:30.675
here's who I will use.

00:24:30.675 --> 00:24:32.050
But the simple
fact of the matter

00:24:32.050 --> 00:24:34.100
is that being married or
being in relationships

00:24:34.100 --> 00:24:37.920
and having those long term
relationships are part of life.

00:24:37.920 --> 00:24:40.330
And that they are a
significant portion of it.

00:24:40.330 --> 00:24:44.460
And almost everybody
has those relationships.

00:24:44.460 --> 00:24:47.340
If you're not showing
those, then you

00:24:47.340 --> 00:24:49.260
are not accurately
reflecting life.

00:24:49.260 --> 00:24:51.260
And people are like, well,
it's science fiction,

00:24:51.260 --> 00:24:53.410
you don't really have to
accurately reflect life.

00:24:53.410 --> 00:24:55.360
Which is a rotten lie.

00:24:55.360 --> 00:24:58.210
I mean, you can actually
talk about the future

00:24:58.210 --> 00:25:00.510
and you can speculate and
you can do whatever you want.

00:25:00.510 --> 00:25:07.680
But at the end of the day, the
human creature is important.

00:25:07.680 --> 00:25:10.260
We have all this technology
now that's amazing.

00:25:10.260 --> 00:25:12.390
We'll have all this
technology in the future.

00:25:12.390 --> 00:25:18.500
Humans are the same build that
they were 30,000 years ago,

00:25:18.500 --> 00:25:19.820
as far as it goes.

00:25:19.820 --> 00:25:25.860
So not having those things
that humans do in your books,

00:25:25.860 --> 00:25:28.299
eventually, it makes
it feel artificial.

00:25:28.299 --> 00:25:30.090
It was also really
important from the point

00:25:30.090 --> 00:25:32.480
of view of that particular
character, John Perry,

00:25:32.480 --> 00:25:36.640
to establish some of what
he was leaving behind.

00:25:36.640 --> 00:25:41.110
So much of who he was was about
who he was with that someone

00:25:41.110 --> 00:25:43.060
else-- with his wife.

00:25:43.060 --> 00:25:47.190
And so it made leaving the
earth that much more, because he

00:25:47.190 --> 00:25:52.610
was leaving that aspect of his
life behind or so he thought.

00:25:52.610 --> 00:25:54.910
The other thing
is that also when

00:25:54.910 --> 00:25:56.410
you write a military
science fiction

00:25:56.410 --> 00:25:59.510
book like I did
with guns and lasers

00:25:59.510 --> 00:26:02.490
and explosions and aliens
who want to eat you

00:26:02.490 --> 00:26:05.335
and all that sort of stuff, you
have a really good opportunity

00:26:05.335 --> 00:26:07.620
to lose like three-quarters
of your audience

00:26:07.620 --> 00:26:10.960
right away if you start
off with a scene, you know,

00:26:10.960 --> 00:26:14.810
where Hunky McChesty
starts shooting

00:26:14.810 --> 00:26:18.562
the aliens with his big zapper
gun and all that sort of stuff

00:26:18.562 --> 00:26:20.270
and it's just blood,
blood, blood, blood.

00:26:20.270 --> 00:26:24.350
I wanted to show--
I intentionally

00:26:24.350 --> 00:26:28.480
did the first scene of
this action-adventure story

00:26:28.480 --> 00:26:30.490
with a guy missing his wife.

00:26:30.490 --> 00:26:33.260
Because that is something
everybody-- anybody who's

00:26:33.260 --> 00:26:36.800
been in a relationship, can you
think about losing your spouse

00:26:36.800 --> 00:26:38.940
or losing your longtime partner?

00:26:38.940 --> 00:26:40.977
It just rips your heart out.

00:26:40.977 --> 00:26:43.310
I mean, I'm getting kind of
choked up thinking about it.

00:26:43.310 --> 00:26:47.100
And so, everybody has that
moment that all of the sudden,

00:26:47.100 --> 00:26:49.270
you're thrown in, you
understand this guy.

00:26:49.270 --> 00:26:51.770
And you will follow
his story because you

00:26:51.770 --> 00:26:54.230
know how much he
misses his wife.

00:26:54.230 --> 00:26:57.659
So that was part
the reason to do it.

