00:27:33.330 --> 00:27:34.985
JOHN SCALZI: Because
it's awesome.

00:27:34.985 --> 00:27:35.860
Because it's awesome.

00:27:35.860 --> 00:27:39.090
Because Amber did
a fantastic job.

00:27:39.090 --> 00:27:43.440
And that, Amber's
way of doing Chris

00:27:43.440 --> 00:27:45.690
is different than Will's
way of doing Chris.

00:27:45.690 --> 00:27:47.377
And both of those
ways of doing Chrises

00:27:47.377 --> 00:27:49.460
are slightly different
than my way of doing Chris.

00:27:49.460 --> 00:27:54.430
You're right, when I originally
wrote Chris and in the book,

00:27:54.430 --> 00:27:56.860
Chris nowhere in
there is gendered.

00:27:56.860 --> 00:27:58.729
And there's a reason for that.

00:27:58.729 --> 00:28:00.270
Part of it is because
I wanted to see

00:28:00.270 --> 00:28:03.180
where people assigned Chris.

00:28:03.180 --> 00:28:05.230
What are your defaults
as a human being?

00:28:05.230 --> 00:28:08.490
And the answer is,
you'll find out,

00:28:08.490 --> 00:28:09.900
by how you respond to Chris.

00:28:09.900 --> 00:28:13.559
My wife read Chris and I did the
thing-- because I automatically

00:28:13.559 --> 00:28:15.350
just sort of, when I'm
talking about people

00:28:15.350 --> 00:28:18.770
in a nonspecific way, just sort
of automatically gender male

00:28:18.770 --> 00:28:21.020
because that's what we do.

00:28:21.020 --> 00:28:22.890
And that's what I
got brought up with.

00:28:22.890 --> 00:28:27.890
Literally, the style guide for
AP and Chicago and everyone

00:28:27.890 --> 00:28:29.899
else said, when in
doubt, gender male.

00:28:29.899 --> 00:28:31.190
So I will still slip into that.

00:28:31.190 --> 00:28:33.080
And one time, I slipped
in that with Chris.

00:28:33.080 --> 00:28:34.480
And she's was like, what?

00:28:34.480 --> 00:28:36.240
No.

00:28:36.240 --> 00:28:38.826
Chris is emphatically
female for her.

00:28:38.826 --> 00:28:42.080
For other people, Chris
is emphatically male.

00:28:42.080 --> 00:28:44.077
What it comes down
to is, really,

00:28:44.077 --> 00:28:45.660
what your own reading
comes out of it.

00:28:45.660 --> 00:28:48.450
And I put that in
there for the purpose

00:28:48.450 --> 00:28:52.176
of making it interesting,
making it kind of exciting.

00:28:52.176 --> 00:28:53.800
But I also didn't
tell people about it.

00:28:53.800 --> 00:28:55.216
It's coming out
now because people

00:28:55.216 --> 00:28:57.770
are like-- thousands of
people have read the book now

00:28:57.770 --> 00:28:59.975
and they're like,
hey, I was confused.

00:29:02.770 --> 00:29:04.060
I need guidance.

00:29:04.060 --> 00:29:07.550
And I'm not offering
any sort of guidance.

00:29:07.550 --> 00:29:10.190
When I wrote Chris, I
specifically was like,

00:29:10.190 --> 00:29:12.100
I'm not going to go there.

00:29:12.100 --> 00:29:13.440
Chris could be male.

00:29:13.440 --> 00:29:14.460
Chris could be female.

00:29:14.460 --> 00:29:16.490
Chris could be intersex.

00:29:16.490 --> 00:29:19.570
Chris could be trans--
started one, went the other,

00:29:19.570 --> 00:29:20.990
maybe went the other direction.

00:29:20.990 --> 00:29:24.567
Maybe Chris has decided
that gender is not a thing

00:29:24.567 --> 00:29:26.150
to be considered at
all, that it's not

00:29:26.150 --> 00:29:29.630
necessary in the construct
that Chris exists in.

00:29:29.630 --> 00:29:33.010
Because Chris is a
Threep to most people.

00:29:33.010 --> 00:29:36.760
And in the Agora, which
is the online world

00:29:36.760 --> 00:29:39.440
that the Hadens are, you can
be anybody who you want to be.

00:29:39.440 --> 00:29:41.990
So this is essentialism
towards gender

00:29:41.990 --> 00:29:45.550
is not necessarily a construct
that works in the same way

00:29:45.550 --> 00:29:48.710
as it works in the
physical world.

00:29:48.710 --> 00:29:51.490
So when it comes
down to the readings

00:29:51.490 --> 00:29:54.870
that Will and Amber
did, they both read

00:29:54.870 --> 00:29:57.370
from their gender
essentialist point of view.

00:29:57.370 --> 00:30:00.240
And so it's really
interesting for me

00:30:00.240 --> 00:30:02.320
to get the back and forth.

00:30:02.320 --> 00:30:05.190
And I say you should listen to
Amber's-- aside from her doing

00:30:05.190 --> 00:30:10.450
a fantastic job-- to see how
you respond to Chris making that

00:30:10.450 --> 00:30:10.950
switch.

00:30:10.950 --> 00:30:12.390
You know?

00:30:12.390 --> 00:30:13.860
Does it change
the story for you?

00:30:13.860 --> 00:30:16.444
Does it change the power
dynamic between Chris and them?

00:30:16.444 --> 00:30:18.360
Does it change the power
dynamic between Chris

00:30:18.360 --> 00:30:21.400
and the other people that
Chris associates with?

00:30:21.400 --> 00:30:23.764
And the answer is,
that will be up to you.

00:30:23.764 --> 00:30:26.180
Again, you don't want to hit
people over the head with it.

00:30:26.180 --> 00:30:27.960
Like I said, I didn't
mention it at all

00:30:27.960 --> 00:30:30.210
until other people
started to mention it.

00:30:30.210 --> 00:30:33.250
Because I didn't want it to
get in the way of the story.

00:30:33.250 --> 00:30:35.166
I wanted it to be the
thing that you noticed

00:30:35.166 --> 00:30:36.540
after you were
done with a story.

00:30:36.540 --> 00:30:39.975
Like, that story was cool,
Chris is-- what is Chris?

00:30:39.975 --> 00:30:41.010
Oh, shit.

00:30:41.010 --> 00:30:41.840
You know?

00:30:41.840 --> 00:30:46.440
And then it kind of blows your
mind and you go off from there.

00:30:46.440 --> 00:30:48.460
So yeah, listen to
Amber and see how

00:30:48.460 --> 00:30:50.611
it changes the main
character for you.

00:30:50.611 --> 00:30:51.110
There we go.

