the ground rules are set,

00:32:06.982 --> 00:32:09.190
that people understand the
rules of the road in terms

00:32:09.190 --> 00:32:13.710
of the communication, and is
able to direct people when they

00:32:13.710 --> 00:32:16.870
get off topic, remove the
trolls when they show up

00:32:16.870 --> 00:32:19.610
as they so often do,
and basically make sure

00:32:19.610 --> 00:32:21.890
that the conversation
that is being had

00:32:21.890 --> 00:32:23.770
is the conversation
that is worth

00:32:23.770 --> 00:32:27.100
having on that particular topic.

00:32:27.100 --> 00:32:33.260
Now, how do you do that
without going too far

00:32:33.260 --> 00:32:36.100
and just basically shutting
down the conversation

00:32:36.100 --> 00:32:37.800
or not doing enough
and just basically

00:32:37.800 --> 00:32:40.730
having it go discursive
all over the place?

00:32:40.730 --> 00:32:44.160
And a lot of it comes down to
practice, practice, practice,

00:32:44.160 --> 00:32:46.830
which is the thing that
most people don't have.

00:32:46.830 --> 00:32:47.450
You know?

00:32:47.450 --> 00:32:49.200
The simple fact of the
matter is that I've

00:32:49.200 --> 00:32:52.650
been doing whatever
for close to 16 years--

00:32:52.650 --> 00:32:55.872
16 years on the 13th, right?

00:32:55.872 --> 00:32:57.080
I been doing this since 1998.

00:32:57.080 --> 00:33:02.470
It is paleo as far as the
internet is concerned.

00:33:02.470 --> 00:33:03.915
I'm Cretaceous period.

00:33:03.915 --> 00:33:05.340
You know?

00:33:05.340 --> 00:33:07.720
But because I've been
doing it for a long time,

00:33:07.720 --> 00:33:10.180
those rhythms are established.

00:33:10.180 --> 00:33:13.730
Most people don't have
the same amount of time

00:33:13.730 --> 00:33:15.790
to devote to it as I do.

00:33:15.790 --> 00:33:18.832
And they don't have the
same sort of either practice

00:33:18.832 --> 00:33:19.790
or rhetorical training.

00:33:19.790 --> 00:33:22.680
Because I also have a degree
in philosophy and rhetoric

00:33:22.680 --> 00:33:24.020
and stuff like that.

00:33:24.020 --> 00:33:29.310
So that a lot of the
detailed instructions

00:33:29.310 --> 00:33:31.100
about how to do
this are not there.

00:33:31.100 --> 00:33:34.520
And I guess one of the things
that maybe Google+ or anybody

00:33:34.520 --> 00:33:39.280
else who wants to foster these
sorts of things can do is, A,

00:33:39.280 --> 00:33:41.690
make sure that the people who
are leading the discussions

00:33:41.690 --> 00:33:46.920
have a robust set of tools
to deal with discursiveness

00:33:46.920 --> 00:33:49.881
so that they actually
own the conversation.

00:33:49.881 --> 00:33:52.380
The other thing that I would
say would probably be useful is

00:33:52.380 --> 00:33:58.260
somewhere online just say,
how to comment on Google+,

00:33:58.260 --> 00:33:59.817
how to have a conversation.

00:33:59.817 --> 00:34:02.400
And in one sort of sense, it's
like wow, that seems insulting.

00:34:02.400 --> 00:34:04.580
But on the other hand, I
have it up on my website.

00:34:04.580 --> 00:34:06.140
It's like, how to
be a good comment.

00:34:06.140 --> 00:34:08.110
It's like, are you on topic?

00:34:08.110 --> 00:34:10.590
Are you doing what I call the
Libertarian dismount, which

00:34:10.590 --> 00:34:13.590
is the thing where
someone-- I'm sorry,

00:34:13.590 --> 00:34:15.239
you're clearly
confused about this.

00:34:15.239 --> 00:34:17.007
The Libertarian
dismount would be,

00:34:17.007 --> 00:34:18.840
like, we're talking
about same-sex marriage.

00:34:18.840 --> 00:34:21.520
And someone goes, well,
that's just because, frankly,

00:34:21.520 --> 00:34:25.000
the state shouldn't be involved
in the marriage process at all.

00:34:25.000 --> 00:34:27.350
And that's fascinating,
but that's not the topic.

00:34:27.350 --> 00:34:30.360
You're dragging this
topic over to the thing

00:34:30.360 --> 00:34:33.050
you want to talk about, which is
whether or not the state should

00:34:33.050 --> 00:34:35.590
be involved with
marriage at all.

00:34:35.590 --> 00:34:40.560
Which is not the topic of how
do we deal with the emerging

00:34:40.560 --> 00:34:43.400
consensus about
same-sex marriage.

00:34:43.400 --> 00:34:45.239
And so, that sort
of dismount into,

00:34:45.239 --> 00:34:46.719
I'm uncomfortable
with this topic,

00:34:46.719 --> 00:34:48.290
so I really want
to talk about this.

00:34:48.290 --> 00:34:50.364
And I'm going to make
you all talk about that,

00:34:50.364 --> 00:34:51.530
is something you don't want.

00:34:51.530 --> 00:34:53.340
Knowing when to quit.

00:34:53.340 --> 00:34:56.830
Knowing when to
have the final word.

00:34:56.830 --> 00:34:58.160
Knowing when to walk away.

00:34:58.160 --> 00:35:00.411
These are all things that
actually have to be learned.

00:35:00.411 --> 00:35:02.160
And some people don't
want to learn those.

00:35:02.160 --> 00:35:03.640
Some people do
want to be trolls.

00:35:03.640 --> 00:35:07.910
Or some people don't think
that their point of view

00:35:07.910 --> 00:35:09.729
is ever possibly wrong.

00:35:09.729 --> 00:35:11.520
They don't even mean
it in a malicious way.

00:35:11.520 --> 00:35:14.340
They just don't understand
why, through the process

00:35:14.340 --> 00:35:16.700
of continually talking
and never shutting up,

00:35:16.700 --> 00:35:20.250
you don't eventually come
around their point of view.

00:35:20.250 --> 00:35:23.112
Yeah, who knew that
that would happen out

00:35:23.112 --> 00:35:24.820
on the internet, where
you don't actually

00:35:24.820 --> 00:35:27.570
have that face-to-face
communication?

00:35:27.570 --> 00:35:30.200
So a lot of that really
will come down to,

00:35:30.200 --> 00:35:34.732
you give the people the tools,
you do as much as you can do.

00:35:34.732 --> 00:35:36.440
But sooner or later,
it's the whole thing

00:35:36.440 --> 00:35:37.690
of leading the horse to water.

00:35:37.690 --> 00:35:41.250
Sooner or later, the horse
either has to drink or not.

00:35:41.250 --> 00:35:42.900
And I would say
give as many tools

00:35:42.900 --> 00:35:45.290
as you can to allow
people to have

00:35:45.290 --> 00:35:46.830
those robust conversations.

00:35:46.830 --> 00:35:49.950
Highlight when and where you
see robust conversations.

00:35:49.950 --> 00:35:52.840
If you go MetaFilter,
they'll have that-- you know,

00:35:52.840 --> 00:35:54.590
Matt Houghey has that
list on the side of,

00:35:54.590 --> 00:35:56.420
these are really
cool conversations

00:35:56.420 --> 00:35:58.710
that we're having a MetaFilter.

00:35:58.710 --> 00:36:00.600
Those are perfect examples.

00:36:00.600 --> 00:36:03.870
And you just train people
over the course of time.

00:36:03.870 --> 00:36:07.330
It's not something that's
going to immediately happen.

00:36:07.330 --> 00:36:10.166
It has to happen over the space
of years and years and years.

00:36:10.166 --> 00:36:11.790
And the problem is
that then you always

00:36:11.790 --> 00:36:13.160
have new people coming in.

00:36:13.160 --> 00:36:16.960
There's an old term
from the Usenet days

00:36:16.960 --> 00:36:21.620
that-- what is it-- the
September that never ends?

00:36:21.620 --> 00:36:26.644
Which was when, every year,
new kids would come to colleges

00:36:26.644 --> 00:36:28.810
and they would get on the
Usenet for the first time.

00:36:28.810 --> 00:36:30.600
And then everyone had
to go, oh, it's time

00:36:30.600 --> 00:36:32.380
to train them how to use it.

00:36:32.380 --> 00:36:35.820
And then AOL-- bless
its heart-- dumped

00:36:35.820 --> 00:36:39.620
all it's 20 million people
on the internet all at once.

00:36:39.620 --> 00:36:42.580
And it was just
September everywhere.

00:36:42.580 --> 00:36:46.200
And so you have a continual
September going on with any

00:36:46.200 --> 00:36:49.011
social media, whether it's
Google+ or Twitter or Facebook

00:36:49.011 --> 00:36:49.510
or whatever.

00:36:49.510 --> 00:36:51.442
Everybody, sooner or
later, cycles through.

00:36:51.442 --> 00:36:53.775
And you just have to accept
that that's part of the deal

00:36:53.775 --> 00:36:54.994
as well.

00:36:54.994 --> 00:36:57.160
That's what I think, and
I'll be sending you a bill.

00:37:00.799 --> 00:37:02.840
AUDIENCE: Hey, another
question about audiobooks.

00:37:02.840 --> 00:37:05.790
I'm kind of interested in
how the audiobook production

00:37:05.790 --> 00:37:08.850
process ties into
writing, if at all.

00:37:08.850 --> 00:37:11.125
Does it just come that
you finish a book,

00:37:11.125 --> 00:37:12.750
throw it over the
wall to Will Wheaton?

00:37:12.750 --> 00:37:14.735
Or is it something
more involved?

00:37:14.735 --> 00:37:17.210
Do you think about that
while you're producing?

00:37:17.210 --> 00:37:18.610
Does this like
effect your choice

00:37:18.610 --> 00:37:20.620
of first versus
third person at all?

00:37:20.620 --> 00:37:21.300
JOHN SCALZI: I'm
sorry, I'm stuck

00:37:21.300 --> 00:37:22.560
on the image of
me chucking things

00:37:22.560 --> 00:37:23.601
over Will Wheaton's wall.

00:37:30.250 --> 00:37:34.020
Actually, I will give
an example of something

00:37:34.020 --> 00:37:37.620
that I do less
now, because I know

00:37:37.620 --> 00:37:42.250
that audio is important to a
large segment of my audience.

00:37:42.250 --> 00:37:45.720
Which is dialogue tags.

00:37:45.720 --> 00:37:48.480
"Let's go down to the
store," Chris said.

00:37:48.480 --> 00:37:50.630
"All right," Christine said.

00:37:50.630 --> 00:37:55.730
"Well, make sure that we
get Coca-Cola," Chris said.

00:37:55.730 --> 00:38:00.120
And the thing is, is when you're
writing that, the he said,

00:38:00.120 --> 00:38:03.444
she said, he said, your
brain filters it out.

00:38:03.444 --> 00:38:05.610
Because enough of it, you're
like, yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:38:05.610 --> 00:38:08.070
The dialogue tag is there
almost in a subliminal way

00:38:08.070 --> 00:38:09.990
to let you know who is talking.

00:38:09.990 --> 00:38:12.250
So in a printed
medium, the fact that I

00:38:12.250 --> 00:38:15.600
put said at the
end of everything

00:38:15.600 --> 00:38:19.090
doesn't really affect things.

00:38:19.090 --> 00:38:24.150
In audiobook, it gets
astoundingly monotonous.

00:38:24.150 --> 00:38:26.730
And I didn't-- people started
saying this to me once

00:38:26.730 --> 00:38:30.109
Will's versions of
stuff of mine took off.

00:38:30.109 --> 00:38:31.650
And they're like,
you use said a lot.

00:38:31.650 --> 00:38:32.470
And I'm like, no, I don't.

00:38:32.470 --> 00:38:32.740
I don't really.

00:38:32.740 --> 00:38:35.230
And then I listened to-- I
was listening to "Red Shirts."

00:38:35.230 --> 00:38:37.890
and there was like a
part in chapter two.

00:38:37.890 --> 00:38:40.940
It's like, blah,
blah, blah, Doll said.

00:38:40.940 --> 00:38:42.600
Blah, blah, blah,
blah, Hanson said.

00:38:42.600 --> 00:38:44.680
I was like, who is this idiot?

00:38:44.680 --> 00:38:46.510
Who is the idiot
who wrote this crap?

00:38:46.510 --> 00:38:48.530
I need to talk to him.

00:38:48.530 --> 00:38:51.760
Because what works in one
medium doesn't necessarily

00:38:51.760 --> 00:38:53.430
work in another medium.

00:38:53.430 --> 00:38:55.810
So for "Lock In,"
because I knew that it

00:38:55.810 --> 00:39:00.180
was going to be done
in audio, I took out

00:39:00.180 --> 00:39:03.730
I would say, probably 30%
40% of the dialogue tags.

00:39:03.730 --> 00:39:05.910
Where if it's just
like two characters

00:39:05.910 --> 00:39:09.370
having a conversation, it'll
be Chris said, John said.

00:39:09.370 --> 00:39:11.380
And then the next
time I go to Chris,

00:39:11.380 --> 00:39:13.500
it doesn't have a
dialogue tag because that

00:39:13.500 --> 00:39:16.750
is the logical place
for that to be going.

00:39:16.750 --> 00:39:20.380
And so, in that
respect, yes absolutely.

00:39:20.380 --> 00:39:23.530
That is one example
of how my writing has

00:39:23.530 --> 00:39:27.030
accommodated this other medium.

00:39:27.030 --> 00:39:29.600
Now, whether it's enough for
people who really dislike

00:39:29.600 --> 00:39:31.290
the fact that I use
that dialogue tag,

00:39:31.290 --> 00:39:32.150
we'll have to see.

00:39:32.150 --> 00:39:35.930
But yeah, you are
aware, no matter

00:39:35.930 --> 00:39:38.740
what you're doing,
where your audience is

00:39:38.740 --> 00:39:40.620
and what their expectations are.

00:39:40.620 --> 00:39:42.430
And to the extent that
it doesn't actually

00:39:42.430 --> 00:39:44.410
compromise your story
or compromise what

00:39:44.410 --> 00:39:47.440
is that you want to do, you
want to accommodate that,

00:39:47.440 --> 00:39:49.870
because you want them
to buy your stuff so you

00:39:49.870 --> 00:39:52.480
could make your
mortgage payment.

00:39:52.480 --> 00:39:55.240
So frankly, I was
happy to do that

00:39:55.240 --> 00:39:57.951
and to incorporate that in.

00:39:57.951 --> 00:39:59.700
And there are other
things that probably I

00:39:59.700 --> 00:40:02.060
do now that I'm not aware of.

00:40:02.060 --> 00:40:04.934
But since I've been
listening to Will and Amber

00:40:04.934 --> 00:40:07.600
and William Dufris, who does the
"Old Man's War" stuff and Tavia

00:40:07.600 --> 00:40:10.020
Gilbert who did "Zoe's
Tale", listening to them

00:40:10.020 --> 00:40:14.650
do my stories, you
definitely soak that in

00:40:14.650 --> 00:40:16.870
and you find out new
things about yourself

00:40:16.870 --> 00:40:20.390
as a writer because of it.

00:40:20.390 --> 00:40:22.464
Come on down.

00:40:22.464 --> 00:40:24.630
AUDIENCE: You've talked
online before about that you

00:40:24.630 --> 00:40:26.200
deliberately make
your novels very,

00:40:26.200 --> 00:40:27.450
like, approachable to readers.

00:40:27.450 --> 00:40:29.200
And it's definitely
something I've noticed

00:40:29.200 --> 00:40:30.940
and you're sort of
the author I recommend

00:40:30.940 --> 00:40:32.820
to non-science fiction
fans just to kind of get

00:40:32.820 --> 00:40:33.695
into science fiction.

00:40:33.695 --> 00:40:35.250
Do you think science
fiction needs

00:40:35.250 --> 00:40:39.305
to do more of that-- needs to
grow beyond its genre roots?

00:40:39.305 --> 00:40:41.010
And where is that
line kind of blurring

00:40:41.010 --> 00:40:43.630
at the moment, between things
that sit in the science fiction

00:40:43.630 --> 00:40:47.100
section of the bookstore
versus a general novel?

00:40:47.100 --> 00:40:52.037
JOHN SCALZI: I do think science
fiction could do with some more

00:40:52.037 --> 00:40:53.370
sort of gateway science fiction.

00:40:53.370 --> 00:40:55.000
I'm torn, because in
one sort of sense,

00:40:55.000 --> 00:40:56.840
there is not a huge amount
of gateway science fiction

00:40:56.840 --> 00:40:59.006
out there, which is great
for me because I write it.

00:40:59.006 --> 00:41:00.647
So I end up being
recommended a lot.

00:41:00.647 --> 00:41:01.980
It was like, what should I read?

00:41:01.980 --> 00:41:03.060
I don't read a lot
of science fiction.

00:41:03.060 --> 00:41:03.790
Scalzi.

00:41:03.790 --> 00:41:05.770
Anybody else?

00:41:05.770 --> 00:41:06.270
No.

00:41:09.720 --> 00:41:11.199
So that's awesome.

00:41:11.199 --> 00:41:13.240
On the other hand, it's
not necessarily very good

00:41:13.240 --> 00:41:14.510
for the genre.

00:41:14.510 --> 00:41:17.150
The thing about it
is that if it has

00:41:17.150 --> 00:41:18.760
to be working on
all sorts of levels.

00:41:18.760 --> 00:41:23.030
You need people like me who are
writing the gateway fiction.

00:41:23.030 --> 00:41:26.080
It's kind of going,
hey, just one hit.

00:41:26.080 --> 00:41:27.405
It'll be fine.

00:41:27.405 --> 00:41:29.030
And the next thing
you know-- you know.

00:41:29.030 --> 00:41:32.340
Then you need people who are
doing the next level of science

00:41:32.340 --> 00:41:34.600
fiction, where the water
is a little deeper,

00:41:34.600 --> 00:41:37.050
things are a little
more complex.

00:41:37.050 --> 00:41:38.490
And then, eventually
you lead them

00:41:38.490 --> 00:41:41.910
down the path that takes them
to Charlie Strauss and China

00:41:41.910 --> 00:41:43.310
Mieville, right?

00:41:43.310 --> 00:41:46.150
And then, once they're there,
they're trapped, right?

00:41:46.150 --> 00:41:48.910
They will never escape
that hole-- the Venus fly

00:41:48.910 --> 00:41:51.804
trap of science
fiction and fantasy.

00:41:51.804 --> 00:41:53.970
But I think it needs to
operate on all those levels.

00:41:53.970 --> 00:41:57.727
You can't just have everything
be open and accessible and fun,

00:41:57.727 --> 00:42:00.060
because then the people who
are really dyed-in-the-wool,

00:42:00.060 --> 00:42:03.367
heavy science fiction fans
are just going to sit there

00:42:03.367 --> 00:42:04.200
and roll their eyes.

00:42:04.200 --> 00:42:08.240
There are people who won't
read me because they're like,

00:42:08.240 --> 00:42:12.040
Scalzi, take off
the training wheels.

00:42:12.040 --> 00:42:14.550
And that's perfectly reasonable.

00:42:14.550 --> 00:42:16.690
It's like, I'm not
writing for them.

00:42:16.690 --> 00:42:18.590
But there are other
people who, you

00:42:18.590 --> 00:42:21.595
know-- if I tried to hand my
mother-in-law-- who I love

00:42:21.595 --> 00:42:25.270
and who reads Julie Garwood and
Nora Roberts-- hand her Charlie

00:42:25.270 --> 00:42:28.130
Strauss or hand her China
Mieville-- both of whom

00:42:28.130 --> 00:42:31.389
are writers that I
think are fabulous

00:42:31.389 --> 00:42:33.430
and have created some of
the best science fiction

00:42:33.430 --> 00:42:37.710
work of the new
century-- she would

00:42:37.710 --> 00:42:41.620
like read for maybe
about five pages

00:42:41.620 --> 00:42:43.900
and she would set it down
and never do that again.

00:42:43.900 --> 00:42:45.830
You have to have all
that work in all levels

00:42:45.830 --> 00:42:48.950
if the field is
going to be healthy.

00:42:48.950 --> 00:42:52.557
So I do think we need more
people doing stuff like me.

00:42:52.557 --> 00:42:54.390
We need more people
doing stuff like Charlie

00:42:54.390 --> 00:42:57.750
and more people doing stuff
like Kameron Hurley, who

00:42:57.750 --> 00:43:02.510
is doing some fantasy right
now which is very complex.

00:43:02.510 --> 00:43:05.300
We need more people like
her doing stuff like that.

00:43:05.300 --> 00:43:09.200
Ann Leckie, who just
won every single award

00:43:09.200 --> 00:43:12.180
imaginable for
"Ancillary Justice,"

00:43:12.180 --> 00:43:16.750
we need more of people like
her who are taking space opera

00:43:16.750 --> 00:43:19.940
and just basically breaking
it apart and putting it

00:43:19.940 --> 00:43:21.640
back together again
in new formats.

00:43:21.640 --> 00:43:24.390
We need more of
everything is basically

00:43:24.390 --> 00:43:26.280
my feeling about science
fiction and fantasy.

00:43:26.280 --> 00:43:28.160
So hopefully we're
in the place where

00:43:28.160 --> 00:43:30.017
we'll get some more of that.

00:43:30.017 --> 00:43:32.100
AUDIENCE: So, I love the
"Old Man's War" universe,

00:43:32.100 --> 00:43:35.770
and I look forward to
more books in that genre.

00:43:35.770 --> 00:43:38.480
But how, as an
author, do you decide

00:43:38.480 --> 00:43:41.090
when to continue
expanding the universe?

00:43:41.090 --> 00:43:43.444
And when you kind of don't
have anything new to say?

00:43:43.444 --> 00:43:45.610
JOHN SCALZI: That's actually
a really good question,

00:43:45.610 --> 00:43:49.100
because there is that tension.

00:43:49.100 --> 00:43:52.480
Because "Old Man's War"
is very successful.

00:43:52.480 --> 00:43:54.850
You've done very well
for me, thank you.

00:43:54.850 --> 00:43:59.090
I will sit in my hot
tub in honor of you.

00:43:59.090 --> 00:44:02.140
We did just buy a
hot tub, by the way.

00:44:02.140 --> 00:44:05.385
And it's ridiculous.

00:44:05.385 --> 00:44:06.710
It is a ridiculous hot tub.

00:44:06.710 --> 00:44:08.630
I was telling them
earlier, it's a hot tub--

00:44:08.630 --> 00:44:10.230
it's like an RV of hot tubs.

00:44:10.230 --> 00:44:12.920
It's just like it seats seven.

00:44:12.920 --> 00:44:15.299
You can have a TV in
it, it has chilled

00:44:15.299 --> 00:44:16.590
drinks, all this sort of stuff.

00:44:16.590 --> 00:44:19.324
And it's the thing that--
you know that old story,

00:44:19.324 --> 00:44:20.740
if you give a mouse
a cookie, it's

00:44:20.740 --> 00:44:21.940
going to want a glass of milk?

00:44:21.940 --> 00:44:23.481
If you get yourself
a hot tub, you're

00:44:23.481 --> 00:44:25.900
going to want a gazebo
for the hot tub.

00:44:25.900 --> 00:44:27.620
It's a money pit.

00:44:27.620 --> 00:44:30.710
So I'm very excited
about the hot tub.

00:44:30.710 --> 00:44:33.660
So please buy more books
is what I'm trying to say.

00:44:33.660 --> 00:44:35.200
But no, here's the tension.

00:44:35.200 --> 00:44:39.210
On one hand, I could,
quite literally,

00:44:39.210 --> 00:44:41.530
write an "Old Man's War"
book and then something else,

00:44:41.530 --> 00:44:43.905
and then another "Old Man's
War" book and something else,

00:44:43.905 --> 00:44:47.030
and another "Old Man's War"
book, until the cows come home.

00:44:47.030 --> 00:44:48.509
And a lot of people
would buy them.

00:44:48.509 --> 00:44:50.050
And they would get
to the point where

00:44:50.050 --> 00:44:52.570
they're like, oh, you know, "Old
Man's War" 17, whatever it is.

00:44:52.570 --> 00:44:53.986
They'd be like,
oh, you know, it's

00:44:53.986 --> 00:44:57.260
not as good as they were
when he started out.

00:44:57.260 --> 00:44:58.250
But, I guess it's OK.

00:44:58.250 --> 00:44:59.165
You know?

00:44:59.165 --> 00:45:01.840
And I don't want to be that guy.

00:45:01.840 --> 00:45:05.430
For one thing, because
if I'm bored writing,

00:45:05.430 --> 00:45:07.960
which I would get bored writing
if I just kept hacking them

00:45:07.960 --> 00:45:09.640
out, you're going
to be bored reading.

00:45:09.640 --> 00:45:11.470
And you might buy
them out of habit,

00:45:11.470 --> 00:45:12.950
but I don't want you to
buy them out of habit.

00:45:12.950 --> 00:45:14.741
I want you to buy them
because you're like,

00:45:14.741 --> 00:45:17.800
holy crap, this out, this
is new, and I need it now.

00:45:17.800 --> 00:45:19.580
I want to actually
want to get it,

00:45:19.580 --> 00:45:21.735
as opposed to feel sort
of a moral obligation.

00:45:21.735 --> 00:45:23.360
Kind of the way you
felt about watching

00:45:23.360 --> 00:45:25.810
episode three of the Star
Wars prequel trilogy.

00:45:25.810 --> 00:45:29.110
It's like, I've invested
this much time, off we go.

00:45:34.350 --> 00:45:36.360
Are you Vader, yet?

00:45:36.360 --> 00:45:38.650
You know what I mean?

00:45:38.650 --> 00:45:39.440
You were there.

00:45:39.440 --> 00:45:41.870
Yeah, and I don't want that.

00:45:41.870 --> 00:45:43.270
I want you to
actually be excited

00:45:43.270 --> 00:45:44.750
about every new episode.

00:45:44.750 --> 00:45:47.570
And sometimes that means
actually stepping away.

00:45:47.570 --> 00:45:51.180
Like, I did an arc that
started with "Old Man's War"

00:45:51.180 --> 00:45:54.040
and ended with "Last
Colony" and "Zoe's Tale."

00:45:54.040 --> 00:45:58.370
It told the story of John
Perry and his family, right?

00:45:58.370 --> 00:45:59.700
That was a complete art.

00:45:59.700 --> 00:46:02.200
And then, when that was
done, I took five years off

00:46:02.200 --> 00:46:04.230
of the "Old Man's War" series.

00:46:04.230 --> 00:46:06.120
And part of the
reason for that was I

00:46:06.120 --> 00:46:07.900
didn't know where
else to go with it.

00:46:07.900 --> 00:46:10.980
I mean, their story was
told, I put the universe

00:46:10.980 --> 00:46:14.410
in a precarious position, but
I didn't know what that meant.

00:46:14.410 --> 00:46:17.100
And so, I went off
and did other things

00:46:17.100 --> 00:46:19.700
while it was rolling
around in my brain.

00:46:19.700 --> 00:46:22.070
And then I became interested
right around the same time

00:46:22.070 --> 00:46:25.060
that the folks at
Tor were like, we

00:46:25.060 --> 00:46:29.130
would like to do this episodic
project where we do everything

00:46:29.130 --> 00:46:31.060
electronically in
a serial fashion.

00:46:31.060 --> 00:46:34.290
I was like, well,
interestingly enough,

00:46:34.290 --> 00:46:36.390
I was thinking of doing
a series of short stories

00:46:36.390 --> 00:46:37.911
with these characters.

00:46:37.911 --> 00:46:39.410
Why don't we combine
those together?

00:46:39.410 --> 00:46:42.680
And that's how that showed up.

00:46:42.680 --> 00:46:45.060
The second "Human
Division" book,

00:46:45.060 --> 00:46:48.610
which I'm working on right now--
which will be out next year--

00:46:48.610 --> 00:46:51.400
is going to be kind of in the
same sort of boat of things.

00:46:51.400 --> 00:46:53.080
But ultimately,
what's going to happen

00:46:53.080 --> 00:46:55.910
with that is, when those
two books are done,

00:46:55.910 --> 00:46:59.330
I will probably step away from
the "Old Man's War" universe

00:46:59.330 --> 00:47:00.934
again, because I've
got to figure out

00:47:00.934 --> 00:47:02.100
what's going to happen next.

00:47:02.100 --> 00:47:04.016
And I would rather take
the time to figure out

00:47:04.016 --> 00:47:07.440
what's happening next then
to just again hack it out.

00:47:07.440 --> 00:47:11.430
The good news is that apparently
you guys do by my other books.

00:47:11.430 --> 00:47:14.650
This actually just landed on the
New York Times hardcover best

00:47:14.650 --> 00:47:15.940
seller list.

00:47:15.940 --> 00:47:18.164
So I'm like, yes.

00:47:18.164 --> 00:47:19.610
[AUDIENCE APPLAUSE]

00:47:19.610 --> 00:47:21.770
I was like, wow, what a relief.

00:47:21.770 --> 00:47:25.690
But it seems like you
guys are willing to let

00:47:25.690 --> 00:47:28.060
me do other things,
which is the other trap.

00:47:28.060 --> 00:47:31.250
Because the question
becomes, do people love you--

00:47:31.250 --> 00:47:36.360
this is the author neurotic
thing-- do they love me for me

00:47:36.360 --> 00:47:38.450
or do they love
me for my series?

00:47:38.450 --> 00:47:39.670
Right?

00:47:39.670 --> 00:47:42.380
Like, if I write something else,
does that something else become

00:47:42.380 --> 00:47:44.130
like, the band
that goes, "This is

00:47:44.130 --> 00:47:46.060
the title track
of our new album."

00:47:46.060 --> 00:47:47.810
And everybody goes
out to go pee.

00:47:47.810 --> 00:47:49.250
Right?

00:47:49.250 --> 00:47:51.870
Play the hits, which would be
the "Old Man's War" series.

00:47:51.870 --> 00:47:53.636
So fortunately, it
seems like you're

00:47:53.636 --> 00:47:55.010
willing to let me
do other things

00:47:55.010 --> 00:47:56.380
and I really appreciate that.

00:47:56.380 --> 00:47:57.954
But it is a consideration.

00:47:57.954 --> 00:47:59.120
I do have a mortgage to pay.

00:47:59.120 --> 00:48:02.710
I do have a daughter who's going
to go through college one day.

00:48:02.710 --> 00:48:04.932
I want to retire one day.

00:48:04.932 --> 00:48:05.890
All this sort of stuff.

00:48:05.890 --> 00:48:07.040
I have a hot tub.

00:48:07.040 --> 00:48:10.305
So all of these things
conspire to what

00:48:10.305 --> 00:48:11.680
things are going
to be commercial

00:48:11.680 --> 00:48:13.350
and what things
are going to work.

00:48:13.350 --> 00:48:17.230
But you know, for me, I do
have the luxury of saying,

00:48:17.230 --> 00:48:19.000
I'll get back to it
when I get back to it.

00:48:19.000 --> 00:48:21.615
So I might, after the
end of this next book,

00:48:21.615 --> 00:48:23.990
get back to the "Old Man's
War" five years down the line,

00:48:23.990 --> 00:48:25.450
10 years down the
line, wherever.

00:48:25.450 --> 00:48:26.866
But when I get
back to it, it will

00:48:26.866 --> 00:48:28.620
be because I want to
be there as opposed

00:48:28.620 --> 00:48:30.130
to I feel like I
have to be there.

00:48:30.130 --> 00:48:32.005
And I think this should
be the last question,

00:48:32.005 --> 00:48:34.005
and then we'll get
to the signing stuff.

00:48:34.005 --> 00:48:36.480
AUDIENCE: Can you share details
of your non-book projects

00:48:36.480 --> 00:48:37.780
that you're working on?

00:48:37.780 --> 00:48:39.860
JOHN SCALZI: Non-book projects?

00:48:39.860 --> 00:48:43.270
TV, TV, you want to
know about the TV?

00:48:43.270 --> 00:48:45.910
OK, I have two TV projects.

00:48:45.910 --> 00:48:50.230
One is "Old Man's War,"
which is going to be at SyFy.

00:48:53.140 --> 00:48:55.640
Which apparently fills a
lot of people with terror.

00:48:55.640 --> 00:48:57.620
They're like, SyFy,
they do wrestling.

00:48:57.620 --> 00:48:58.870
They don't do science fiction.

00:48:58.870 --> 00:49:01.328
No, they actually have started
doing science fiction again.

00:49:01.328 --> 00:49:04.270
They've got "The Expanse"
series by James S A Corey,

00:49:04.270 --> 00:49:07.560
"The Magicians" by Lev
Grossman, yeah, right?

00:49:07.560 --> 00:49:08.650
Yeah.

00:49:08.650 --> 00:49:10.040
I'm excited about it, too, sir.

00:49:10.040 --> 00:49:13.000
And then, of course,
my book series as well.

00:49:13.000 --> 00:49:16.060
So they seem to be going
all-in about actually living up

00:49:16.060 --> 00:49:17.490
to their network name.

00:49:17.490 --> 00:49:18.910
That's going to be positive.

00:49:18.910 --> 00:49:21.990
"Redshirts" has
been optioned by FX

00:49:21.990 --> 00:49:24.349
as a mini series, which is
kind of cool because they've

00:49:24.349 --> 00:49:26.140
been doing really well
with the miniseries.

00:49:26.140 --> 00:49:28.300
They've just got
nominated for-- and I

00:49:28.300 --> 00:49:33.360
think have won-- quite a few
Emmys for their "Fargo" series,

00:49:33.360 --> 00:49:35.710
as an example of that.

00:49:35.710 --> 00:49:38.530
And those are at the
writing stage right now.

00:49:38.530 --> 00:49:41.761
I've met with the writers for
the "Old Man's War" series.

00:49:41.761 --> 00:49:43.260
Which is also another
reason why I'm

00:49:43.260 --> 00:49:46.380
OK to step back, because in the
meantime, while I'm thinking

00:49:46.380 --> 00:49:51.630
about where it goes next, you'll
have these guys dribbling out

00:49:51.630 --> 00:49:54.740
new episodes of whatever's going
on in the "Old Man's War" world

00:49:54.740 --> 00:49:56.400
and that will be kind of fun.

00:49:56.400 --> 00:49:58.550
And it's fascinating,
because, you know,

00:49:58.550 --> 00:50:00.130
it's a completely
different medium.

00:50:00.130 --> 00:50:02.710
You understand when you go
into that the book is not

00:50:02.710 --> 00:50:04.830
going to be the TV
series, and the TV series

00:50:04.830 --> 00:50:06.437
is not going to be the book.

00:50:06.437 --> 00:50:08.020
And the changes that
they have to make

00:50:08.020 --> 00:50:10.614
because the storytelling
is different.

00:50:10.614 --> 00:50:12.280
The fact that they
actually have to work

00:50:12.280 --> 00:50:13.821
within certain
budgetary constraints,

00:50:13.821 --> 00:50:15.170
and so on and so forth.

00:50:15.170 --> 00:50:16.960
And just the way
that that all works.

00:50:16.960 --> 00:50:18.460
And people are like,
are you worried

00:50:18.460 --> 00:50:19.870
about them changing your books?

00:50:19.870 --> 00:50:20.800
And I'm like, no,
because they're not

00:50:20.800 --> 00:50:21.450
going to change books.

00:50:21.450 --> 00:50:22.650
The books are over here.

00:50:22.650 --> 00:50:24.670
They will always
remain the same.

00:50:24.670 --> 00:50:28.100
I own the copyright on those,
they ain't changing, right?

00:50:28.100 --> 00:50:31.450
But what they do do will
be kind of interesting.

00:50:31.450 --> 00:50:33.850
Now, if they're successful,
it doesn't matter.

00:50:33.850 --> 00:50:36.380
Because what they do to the
series in some sort of way,

00:50:36.380 --> 00:50:38.400
because the books will take off.

00:50:38.400 --> 00:50:45.540
Like, you may have heard of
this guy, George Martin, right?

00:50:45.540 --> 00:50:50.640
He's got this little series on
HBO called "Game of Thrones."

00:50:50.640 --> 00:50:54.370
His books are just
this huge clot

00:50:54.370 --> 00:50:57.980
at the top of the best
seller lists in paperback.

00:50:57.980 --> 00:51:00.710
It's like every
month, in and out,

00:51:00.710 --> 00:51:03.900
you've got all like--
four out of the six

00:51:03.900 --> 00:51:06.060
books-- I think there's
six, how many books now?

00:51:06.060 --> 00:51:07.340
Five?

00:51:07.340 --> 00:51:10.840
You guys would know.

00:51:10.840 --> 00:51:13.950
Four out of the five--
there's always right up there

00:51:13.950 --> 00:51:15.590
at the top.

00:51:15.590 --> 00:51:18.350
And the thing is that, the
fact that they can just

00:51:18.350 --> 00:51:22.120
wait until season six or
whatever or season five comes

00:51:22.120 --> 00:51:23.910
out doesn't stop the
books from selling.

00:51:23.910 --> 00:51:26.954
So I'm kind of looking
forward to that, you know?

00:51:26.954 --> 00:51:29.610
Because then I will take this
hot tub that I just bought

00:51:29.610 --> 00:51:32.200
and I will fill
it full of money.

00:51:32.200 --> 00:51:35.726
I'll just sit there and
rub the money on me.

00:51:35.726 --> 00:51:36.720
[AUDIENCE LAUGHTER]

00:51:36.720 --> 00:51:38.960
Just like that.

00:51:38.960 --> 00:51:40.890
So that will be really positive.

00:51:40.890 --> 00:51:42.270
So that's one thing.

00:51:42.270 --> 00:51:46.430
I'm also working on a video
game called "Midnight Star"

00:51:46.430 --> 00:51:52.850
with Industrial Toys, which is
a first-person-shooter that's

00:51:52.850 --> 00:51:54.280
designed for tablets.

00:51:54.280 --> 00:51:56.610
So can play a
first-person-shooter literally

00:51:56.610 --> 00:51:57.370
with one hand.

00:51:57.370 --> 00:51:59.710
So on hand holding the
tablet, the other one

00:51:59.710 --> 00:52:02.420
killing all the aliens
and stuff like that.

00:52:02.420 --> 00:52:06.090
One of the principals
of Industrial Toys

00:52:06.090 --> 00:52:09.200
is Alex Seropian, who co-founded
Bungie and co-created Halo.

00:52:09.200 --> 00:52:11.230
So when he called me
up and was like, hey,

00:52:11.230 --> 00:52:13.550
would you like to do
this video game with me?

00:52:13.550 --> 00:52:16.160
I was like, that seems
an acceptable risk.

00:52:16.160 --> 00:52:18.370
So that will
actually hopefully be

00:52:18.370 --> 00:52:19.670
out in the next couple months.

00:52:19.670 --> 00:52:22.360
And I've seen it
and I've played it.

00:52:22.360 --> 00:52:24.557
And it's a hell of a lot of fun.

00:52:24.557 --> 00:52:26.390
And that's what I'm
going to say about that.

00:52:26.390 --> 00:52:29.140
Well, we are at the
two o'clock hour.

00:52:29.140 --> 00:52:32.740
And what I will do now is I
will go to the back of the room

00:52:32.740 --> 00:52:35.170
and I will happily
sign your books.

00:52:35.170 --> 00:52:36.920
Thank you all for
coming and spending

00:52:36.920 --> 00:52:40.000
your free hour with me.

00:52:40.000 --> 00:52:42.150
[APPLAUSE]

